Understanding RBAC: A Pillar of Kubernetes Security

What is RBAC?
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) is a method of regulating access to resources based on the roles of individual users within an organization. In Kubernetes, RBAC is used to define what actions users or service accounts can perform on specific resources in the cluster. It provides a fine-grained control mechanism, ensuring that only authorized entities can access or modify resources.

In Kubernetes, there are two types of accounts:
1.User Account
2.Service Account

1.User account: User accounts are used to log into a Kubernetes cluster and manipulate resources therein. Each user account is associated with a unique set of credentials, which are used to authenticate the service’s requests.

2.Service Account: Kubernetes Service Accounts are specialised accounts used by applications and services running on Kubernetes to interact with the Kubernetes API.

Which account type should you use?

Use a User Account: When a human needs to interact with the Kubernetes cluster, such as developers, admins, or operators using tools like kubectl.

Use a Service Account: When an application or workload running inside the cluster needs to access Kubernetes resources programmatically.

Lets do some hands on:
Lets create a user, But Kubernetes API will not allow us to create user directly. so there are multiple ways to create user

will choose client certificate to create a user which is very easy to create.
This certificates are used to create users. When a user perform any command like kubectl get po then K8's API will authenticate and authorize the request.
authentication: permission to login.
authorization: permission to work on resources.
Steps to create certificate:

lets create a folder:  mkdir random-user && cd random-user
Generate a key using openssl :  openssl genrsa -out random.key 2048
Generate a Client Sign Request (CSR) : openssl req -new -key random.key -out random.csr -subj "/CN=random/O=group1"
Generate the certificate (CRT): openssl x509 -req -in random.csr -CA ~/.minikube/ca.crt -CAkey ~/.minikube/ca.key -CAcreateserial -out random.crt -days 500

Steps to create user.
lets create a user: kubectl config set-credentials random --client-certificate=random.crt --client-key=random.key

Set a context entry in kubeconfig: kubectl config set-context my-context --cluster=minikube --user=random

Context is used to switch the users in K8s cluster. Because in K8s we cant switch using users, we will add users to context and we will use context to switch b/w users.

There are four components to RBAC in Kubernetes:
1.roles
2.Cluster roles
3.role bindings
4.ClusterRolesBinding

Components of RBAC in Kubernetes:
1.roles
2.Cluster roles
3.role bindings
4.ClusterRolesBinding

1.Role: is a set of permissions that define what actions (verbs) are allowed on specific resources (API groups and resources) within a particular Namespace.

2.Role bindings: connect users/groups to roles. For example, you might bind the “admin” role to the “admin” user. This would give the “admin” user all the permissions defined in the “admin” role.
It grants the permissions to particular namespaces only.

3.ClusterRoles: are special roles that apply to all users in the cluster. For example, you might create a ClusterRole called “cluster-admin” that gives the user or group full access to all resources in the cluster. These are not Namespace-specific. They define permissions for cluster-wide resources.

4.ClusterRoleBindings similar to RoleBindings, ClusterRoleBindings associate ClusterRoles with users/groups across the entire cluster.
These are not Namespace-specific. They grants the permissions for cluster-wide resources.

Lets create a namespace called dev :kubectl create ns dev

Now lets create a role that gives permissions to K8s resources:
apiVersion: https://lnkd.in/gDmBgtrj
kind: Role
metadata:
 namespace: dev
 name: dev-role
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
 resources: ["pods"]
 verbs: ["get", "watch", "list"]

apply it:kubectl create -f role.yml
Imperative way : kubectl create role admin --verb=get,list,watch,create,update,delete --resource=pods,deployments -n dev
To check it : kubectl get role -n dev

Now attach this dev-role to user (Role binding):

apiVersion: https://lnkd.in/gDmBgtrj
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
 name: dev-role-binding
 namespace: dev
subjects:
- kind: User
 name: random
 apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
 kind: Role
 name: dev-role
 apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

Working on Cluster Role:
First lets change the context to minikube and go to default namespace
change the contex: kubectl config use-context minikube

Lets create cluster role:
apiVersion: https://lnkd.in/gDmBgtrj
kind: ClusterRole
metadata:
 name: random-cluster-role
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
 resources: ["pods", "deployments"]
 verbs: ["get", "watch", "list", "create"]
- apiGroups: [""]
 resources: ["services"]
 verbs: ["get", "watch", "list", "create", "delete"

Lets create cluster role binding:
apiVersion: https://lnkd.in/gDmBgtrj
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
 name: cluster-role-binding
subjects:
- kind: User
 name: random
 apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
 kind: ClusterRole
 name: random-cluster-role
 apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

